00:42:52.094 --> 00:42:53.510
AUDIENCE: Working
in New York, you

00:42:53.510 --> 00:42:55.160
have a lot of great
partners there--

00:42:55.160 --> 00:43:00.860
Brian Miller, Dale DeGroff,
the late Sasha Petraske.

00:43:00.860 --> 00:43:04.280
Do you have any main influences
while you working there?

00:43:04.280 --> 00:43:05.960
JIM MEEHAN: Yeah.

00:43:05.960 --> 00:43:09.320
When I moved to New York, I
moved to Stanton and Clinton,

00:43:09.320 --> 00:43:12.950
and I was very fortunate to be
there right when wd~50 opened.

00:43:12.950 --> 00:43:17.480
So Eben Freeman was the
head bartender there.

00:43:17.480 --> 00:43:20.270
And Shiller's
Liquor Bar actually

00:43:20.270 --> 00:43:23.960
opened over on Norfolk and
Rivington just maybe a year

00:43:23.960 --> 00:43:24.870
or two after that.

00:43:24.870 --> 00:43:28.400
So I was very fortunate when I
moved there to be able to have

00:43:28.400 --> 00:43:33.140
shift drinks with Eben at wd~50.

00:43:33.140 --> 00:43:37.205
Dewey Dufresne, Wiley's dad,
was a really amazing wine

00:43:37.205 --> 00:43:38.240
and spirits collector.

00:43:38.240 --> 00:43:42.710
And I drank most of the 1900s
armagnac for free during those

00:43:42.710 --> 00:43:44.010
days.

00:43:44.010 --> 00:43:48.920
And Dushan Jaric and Jay Kosmas,
who opened Employees Only,

00:43:48.920 --> 00:43:52.790
the last bar that they worked
out for Keith McNally was

00:43:52.790 --> 00:43:53.640
at Shiller's.

00:43:53.640 --> 00:43:57.660
So between those two bars, it
was sort of really influential

00:43:57.660 --> 00:43:58.160
for me.

00:43:58.160 --> 00:44:01.040
And then my first
sort of aha moment

00:44:01.040 --> 00:44:04.820
was when Eben took me late
one night to Milk and Honey

00:44:04.820 --> 00:44:06.400
in 2003.

00:44:06.400 --> 00:44:08.870
I'll never forget going there.

00:44:08.870 --> 00:44:11.870
Joseph Schwartz, who opened
Little Branch with Sasha

00:44:11.870 --> 00:44:14.177
was working on the
floor, and Toby Maloney,

00:44:14.177 --> 00:44:16.010
who opened the Violet
Hour here and ended up

00:44:16.010 --> 00:44:18.800
opening The Pegu Club as
the head bartender with me,

00:44:18.800 --> 00:44:19.730
was behind the bar.

00:44:19.730 --> 00:44:22.550
And I had a Gold Rush cocktail.

00:44:22.550 --> 00:44:25.730
And it was a drink that TJ
Siegel, who was Sasha's best

00:44:25.730 --> 00:44:26.600
friend, created.

00:44:26.600 --> 00:44:29.120
And it was a simple combination
of bourbon and lemon juice

00:44:29.120 --> 00:44:31.010
and honey.

00:44:31.010 --> 00:44:35.090
Both Toby and Joseph were
wearing the banker's garb.

00:44:35.090 --> 00:44:37.790
And Joseph had this
beautiful silver tray

00:44:37.790 --> 00:44:41.870
with a candle on it.

00:44:41.870 --> 00:44:45.770
And he was just very elegant
and very accommodating

00:44:45.770 --> 00:44:46.670
in the way served it.

00:44:46.670 --> 00:44:49.850
They served this drink to me
in an ice cold Old Fashioned

00:44:49.850 --> 00:44:53.030
glass with a hand-carved
piece of ice.

00:44:53.030 --> 00:44:56.240
Going back to the daiquiri,
it was a perfect sour

00:44:56.240 --> 00:45:00.250
with Eljah Craig and
lemon juice and honey.

00:45:00.250 --> 00:45:01.830
And the environment was amazing.

00:45:01.830 --> 00:45:05.060
One of the things that has been
sort of lost in translation

00:45:05.060 --> 00:45:08.330
as we think about this sort
of modern cocktail renaissance

00:45:08.330 --> 00:45:11.180
is that Milk and Honey,
really, back in those days,

00:45:11.180 --> 00:45:12.050
was a refuge.

00:45:12.050 --> 00:45:15.440
Before apps were the way
that people met each other,

00:45:15.440 --> 00:45:16.970
people met each other in bars.

00:45:16.970 --> 00:45:20.960
And bars were really sort of, in
my opinion, somewhat predatory,

00:45:20.960 --> 00:45:22.580
knuckle-dragging
places where people

00:45:22.580 --> 00:45:25.170
kind of just like glommed onto
each other and got wasted.

00:45:25.170 --> 00:45:28.640
And I didn't really like that.

00:45:28.640 --> 00:45:30.510
Milk and Honey was
like going to church.

00:45:30.510 --> 00:45:36.480
And so that was sort of a huge
game-changing moment for me,

00:45:36.480 --> 00:45:38.780
where I was considering
focusing on wine

00:45:38.780 --> 00:45:40.910
and maybe being a
sommelier when I grew up.

00:45:40.910 --> 00:45:42.729
And I realized
that, at that point,

00:45:42.729 --> 00:45:44.270
I'd been a bartender
for eight years,

00:45:44.270 --> 00:45:47.540
really loved it, and saw
this kind of escape route

00:45:47.540 --> 00:45:49.550
into bartending.

00:45:49.550 --> 00:45:54.050
And so certainly, Sasha
and Joseph and Eben

00:45:54.050 --> 00:45:56.780
were early
inspirations, and then

00:45:56.780 --> 00:46:01.250
obviously Audrey Saunders and
Julie Reiner and many others.

00:46:01.250 --> 00:46:04.550
I think that when you
speak to a lot of sort

00:46:04.550 --> 00:46:06.890
of successful people
or important people,

00:46:06.890 --> 00:46:10.130
they want to tell you that
they were inspired or mentored

00:46:10.130 --> 00:46:13.550
by the most famous people that
they know or ever worked with.

00:46:13.550 --> 00:46:16.370
And I would say,
for me, I've always

00:46:16.370 --> 00:46:18.170
made a point of trying
to learn something

00:46:18.170 --> 00:46:19.610
from everybody I worked with.

00:46:19.610 --> 00:46:22.940
And I would say that every
single person I've worked with

00:46:22.940 --> 00:46:25.250
has taught me something
about my career, about myself

00:46:25.250 --> 00:46:26.280
that I didn't know.

00:46:26.280 --> 00:46:29.480
And I maintain
that if you remain

00:46:29.480 --> 00:46:32.360
open to knowing
more about yourself

00:46:32.360 --> 00:46:36.920
and more about your
craft through being open,

00:46:36.920 --> 00:46:40.220
working with others, I feel
like you continue to learn.

00:46:40.220 --> 00:46:43.470
I was sitting at Prairie
School last time here--

00:46:43.470 --> 00:46:45.470
I've actually never tended
bar at Prairie School

00:46:45.470 --> 00:46:46.967
yet, which, to me, is--

00:46:46.967 --> 00:46:48.800
when I have to tend
bar, I know I've failed.

00:46:48.800 --> 00:46:49.910
AMY STARR: What are you
doing a little later?

00:46:49.910 --> 00:46:51.200
JIM MEEHAN: Thankfully,
you will not see me

00:46:51.200 --> 00:46:52.450
behind the bar tonight either.

00:46:52.450 --> 00:46:54.800
But I watched one
of our partners--

00:46:54.800 --> 00:46:57.380
I believe it was Scott or Ed.

00:46:57.380 --> 00:46:59.844
He was holding both
jiggers in one hand, which

00:46:59.844 --> 00:47:01.760
is something that came
about while I was still

00:47:01.760 --> 00:47:03.730
behind the bar, but
I never did that.

00:47:03.730 --> 00:47:06.560
But in order to do a one
and a half ounce pour, which

00:47:06.560 --> 00:47:10.380
is something that-- you
usually either do something

00:47:10.380 --> 00:47:11.630
I don't really like very much.

00:47:11.630 --> 00:47:15.470
You pour not all the way up to
the top of the two-ounce cup,

00:47:15.470 --> 00:47:19.130
or you have to do 3/4,
3/4, it's a double pour.

00:47:19.130 --> 00:47:20.690
He flipped his
jiggers in such a way

00:47:20.690 --> 00:47:23.540
so it was a one-ounce
cup and a half-ounce cup.

00:47:23.540 --> 00:47:26.900
And he poured into both
the half and one-ounce cup,

00:47:26.900 --> 00:47:29.510
and then dumped both cups
into the mixing glass.

00:47:29.510 --> 00:47:32.210
And I watched him do
that, and I was like,

00:47:32.210 --> 00:47:35.120
I've been doing this since
1995, and I had never

00:47:35.120 --> 00:47:38.180
thought of pouring a one and a
half ounce with two jigger cups

00:47:38.180 --> 00:47:41.390
in my hand and pouring
at the same time.

00:47:41.390 --> 00:47:42.235
It's so simple.

00:47:42.235 --> 00:47:44.360
But it's just something
I'd never seen done before.

00:47:44.360 --> 00:47:47.660
And I think that those moments
for me are very exciting.

00:47:47.660 --> 00:47:49.830
And it's the reason
why I surround myself

00:47:49.830 --> 00:47:53.040
with young smart
people, and why I'm not

00:47:53.040 --> 00:47:56.730
so didactic about the
way things are done.

00:47:56.730 --> 00:47:59.940
I think if you create
enough leeway for people

00:47:59.940 --> 00:48:04.210
to do things their way as
much as they possibly can,

00:48:04.210 --> 00:48:07.185
as the boss, or as the
overseer or operator,

00:48:07.185 --> 00:48:09.810
or, really, as the person who's
responsible for everything that

00:48:09.810 --> 00:48:12.109
goes wrong, you put
yourself in a position

00:48:12.109 --> 00:48:14.400
where you can see people do
things that you never would

00:48:14.400 --> 00:48:16.680
have thought of, because
you gave them the runway

00:48:16.680 --> 00:48:17.430
to take off from.

00:48:23.260 --> 00:48:25.150
AUDIENCE: So outside of
Prairie School, which

00:48:25.150 --> 00:48:26.733
is the best bar in
Chicago, obviously,

00:48:26.733 --> 00:48:28.360
can you give us a
rundown of Chicago?

00:48:28.360 --> 00:48:29.859
What are your spots,
or where do you

00:48:29.859 --> 00:48:32.490
respect, or other cocktail bars,
or even bars, how you said,

00:48:32.490 --> 00:48:35.227
that have that nostalgic,
authentic factor?

00:48:35.227 --> 00:48:37.060
Because I think that's
an interesting angle.

00:48:37.060 --> 00:48:38.830
Obviously, we have
The Aviary right here.

00:48:38.830 --> 00:48:41.500
But there's also a lot
of good local spots,

00:48:41.500 --> 00:48:43.150
and it seems like
you're well-traveled.

00:48:43.150 --> 00:48:43.858
JIM MEEHAN: Yeah.

00:48:43.858 --> 00:48:46.030
I mean, when I was
younger, I went

00:48:46.030 --> 00:48:47.740
to all the bars in
Chicago, and that's

00:48:47.740 --> 00:48:51.160
why I don't go to all the
bars in Chicago anymore.

00:48:51.160 --> 00:48:53.240
All the miles in my
liver have been used up.

00:48:53.240 --> 00:48:55.810
But today was a great example.

00:48:55.810 --> 00:48:57.820
I showed up early
for a treatment

00:48:57.820 --> 00:49:01.690
and was sent around the corner
to a bar called The Map Room.

00:49:01.690 --> 00:49:06.040
And I was sent there
to get a cup of coffee.

00:49:06.040 --> 00:49:08.720
And it's a beer bar, from
what Google tells me.

00:49:08.720 --> 00:49:11.020
And it was amazing.

00:49:11.020 --> 00:49:13.000
Like, I walked
into this beer bar,

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:16.300
and it didn't smell
like a beer bar.

00:49:16.300 --> 00:49:17.414
I sat down at the bar.

00:49:17.414 --> 00:49:18.580
And I looked at the spirits.

00:49:18.580 --> 00:49:20.530
And while all the
bottles in the back bar

00:49:20.530 --> 00:49:24.047
had pour spouts on it,
which is a no-no in my mind,

00:49:24.047 --> 00:49:26.380
all the spirits on the back
bar were really thoughtfully

00:49:26.380 --> 00:49:28.450
chosen, great spirits.

00:49:28.450 --> 00:49:32.230
And the bartender
working, pouring coffee

00:49:32.230 --> 00:49:35.740
was this incredibly,
effusively polite,

00:49:35.740 --> 00:49:39.310
probably Mexican gentleman,
who I order a coffee from.

00:49:39.310 --> 00:49:40.450
It was a black coffee.

00:49:40.450 --> 00:49:41.890
It was an Intelligentsia coffee.

00:49:41.890 --> 00:49:43.630
And I sat in the room.

00:49:43.630 --> 00:49:46.690
And it once again had
that church-like feel.

00:49:46.690 --> 00:49:49.090
And I would say that,
with respect to Chicago,

00:49:49.090 --> 00:49:52.250
certainly there are the
Milk Rooms and the Aviaries

00:49:52.250 --> 00:49:56.910
and the Billy Sundays
and the Violet Hours.

00:49:56.910 --> 00:50:01.540
There are world class bars
that are doing next level

00:50:01.540 --> 00:50:04.600
stuff that I would put up
against the bars in San

00:50:04.600 --> 00:50:06.130
Francisco or New
York, or London.

00:50:06.130 --> 00:50:09.630
But I find that the
taverns that I visit--

00:50:09.630 --> 00:50:11.710
the sort of corner
bars in Chicago--

00:50:11.710 --> 00:50:14.470
are the ones that really
kind of blow me away.

00:50:14.470 --> 00:50:18.550
And I would go back to not
just the Midwestern sense

00:50:18.550 --> 00:50:21.400
of hospitality and
work ethic, but just

00:50:21.400 --> 00:50:25.300
the idea that drinking
in Chicago is a thing.

00:50:25.300 --> 00:50:32.620
Like, there's no guilt.
People have a hedonistic--

00:50:32.620 --> 00:50:33.880
like, Wisconsin's even better.

00:50:33.880 --> 00:50:38.860
But people eat and drink
here like it's not this thing

00:50:38.860 --> 00:50:41.290
that they shouldn't be doing,
or this thing that they're

00:50:41.290 --> 00:50:43.000
doing instead of yoga.

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:44.660
It's this thing that they do--

00:50:44.660 --> 00:50:46.380
AMY STARR: After yoga.

00:50:46.380 --> 00:50:49.820
JIM MEEHAN: Or before
yoga, or instead of yoga.

00:50:49.820 --> 00:50:51.220
Is there yoga?

00:50:51.220 --> 00:50:55.200
And I feel like the
cross-pollination of like great

00:50:55.200 --> 00:50:58.570
bars and operators,
but great guests--

00:50:58.570 --> 00:51:03.070
like, people who really
enthusiastically enjoy bars,

00:51:03.070 --> 00:51:05.770
I feel like, is what makes
drinking in Chicago great.

00:51:05.770 --> 00:51:09.100
There's a symbiotic
relationship between those

00:51:09.100 --> 00:51:11.910
who come to bars and
those who work in bars.

00:51:11.910 --> 00:51:15.580
And I would say that, in
many ways, when I opened PDT,

00:51:15.580 --> 00:51:19.150
I realized very quickly
that my staff was

00:51:19.150 --> 00:51:21.190
fully capable of
making what I thought

00:51:21.190 --> 00:51:22.560
were complicated drinks.

00:51:22.560 --> 00:51:27.580
What really became the challenge
was, in such a small bar,

00:51:27.580 --> 00:51:30.880
how can I do everything
I can to make sure

00:51:30.880 --> 00:51:33.700
that most of my guests
were sympathetic to what

00:51:33.700 --> 00:51:35.150
we were trying to do there.

00:51:35.150 --> 00:51:38.390
Because a couple of
bad people in a bar,

00:51:38.390 --> 00:51:41.320
especially a small bar,
just ruins the vibe.

00:51:41.320 --> 00:51:45.670
And in so many ways, I find that
it's so much easier to run bars

00:51:45.670 --> 00:51:48.100
in Chicago, because
most of the guests

00:51:48.100 --> 00:51:51.970
are nice, reasonable,
good, vibey people.

00:51:54.710 --> 00:51:56.780
Go to the Map Room.

00:51:56.780 --> 00:51:58.940
Have a cup of of black
Intelligentsia coffee.

00:52:01.620 --> 00:52:04.370
AUDIENCE: Let me preface
this question with,

00:52:04.370 --> 00:52:07.030
I used to live in East
Village in New York.

00:52:07.030 --> 00:52:08.044
Love PDT.

00:52:08.044 --> 00:52:08.960
JIM MEEHAN: Thank you.

00:52:08.960 --> 00:52:10.430
AUDIENCE: Didn't go
there nearly as often

00:52:10.430 --> 00:52:12.210
as I'd like to, because
it was too hard to get in.

00:52:12.210 --> 00:52:12.920
JIM MEEHAN: I apologize.

00:52:12.920 --> 00:52:15.140
That's what most people
say on the internet, too.

00:52:15.140 --> 00:52:16.660
AUDIENCE: And I got your book.

00:52:16.660 --> 00:52:17.000
JIM MEEHAN: Thank you.

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:17.870
AUDIENCE: And I
definitely appreciate

00:52:17.870 --> 00:52:19.730
all the thoughtfulness
and hard work

00:52:19.730 --> 00:52:21.560
and production
that went into it.

00:52:21.560 --> 00:52:22.476
JIM MEEHAN: Thank you.

00:52:22.476 --> 00:52:25.460
AUDIENCE: Also, looking forward
to The Aviary's cocktail book.

00:52:25.460 --> 00:52:27.500
JIM MEEHAN: Yeah, their
Kickstarter updates

00:52:27.500 --> 00:52:28.610
are unbelievable.

00:52:28.610 --> 00:52:32.020
AUDIENCE: So with that said,
you mentioned Milk and Honey.

00:52:35.856 --> 00:52:39.252
You usually don't get a
drink that's on a menu.

00:52:39.252 --> 00:52:40.460
JIM MEEHAN: There is no menu.

00:52:40.460 --> 00:52:44.990
AUDIENCE: Yeah, you want
a, how do you feel today?

00:52:44.990 --> 00:52:46.760
You know, bartenders choice.

00:52:46.760 --> 00:52:49.820
So I wanted to hear
your opinion on,

00:52:49.820 --> 00:52:52.090
which direction is
the industry going--

00:52:52.090 --> 00:52:55.670
towards well thought out,
well-named cocktails,

00:52:55.670 --> 00:53:02.030
or creative,
on-the-fly concoctions?

00:53:02.030 --> 00:53:06.950
And what is your opinion
of, which way should it go?

00:53:06.950 --> 00:53:11.750
JIM MEEHAN: Well, I think that,
going back to my "Matrix-y"

00:53:11.750 --> 00:53:14.390
Pacific Northwest answer,
I think it's going in all

00:53:14.390 --> 00:53:15.300
directions.

00:53:15.300 --> 00:53:17.540
The cocktail culture
is growing at this sort

00:53:17.540 --> 00:53:19.310
of exponential pace right now.

00:53:19.310 --> 00:53:21.960
So it is definitely
going in all directions.

00:53:21.960 --> 00:53:24.890
The reason why I
haven't chosen to go

00:53:24.890 --> 00:53:27.110
in the
choose-your-own-adventure,

00:53:27.110 --> 00:53:32.100
"how are you feeling,"
[INAUDIBLE] forked path,

00:53:32.100 --> 00:53:35.195
"let me find you a drink" style
of service that you used to get

00:53:35.195 --> 00:53:37.820
at Milk and Honey, and you still
get at some cocktail bars, is,

00:53:37.820 --> 00:53:44.990
I feel like writing a menu
is actually really hard.

00:53:44.990 --> 00:53:48.226
And coming up with the menu
and changing the menu--

00:53:48.226 --> 00:53:49.850
We have what we call
a [INAUDIBLE] menu

00:53:49.850 --> 00:53:53.140
at Prairie School, where
every two and a half weeks, we

00:53:53.140 --> 00:53:55.170
actually change a
page of our menu.

00:53:55.170 --> 00:53:59.480
We put three new drinks on, a
different black and green tea

00:53:59.480 --> 00:54:02.480
or an oolong or white
tea, and a different food

00:54:02.480 --> 00:54:05.480
dish, and a different
single-origin coffee.

00:54:05.480 --> 00:54:08.040
So that changes every
two and a half weeks.

00:54:08.040 --> 00:54:14.360
And then our full menu
changes, not in its entirety,

00:54:14.360 --> 00:54:16.850
quarterly, sort of in an
American seasonal set.

00:54:16.850 --> 00:54:22.280
So I would say that, for
me, my interest has always

00:54:22.280 --> 00:54:28.040
been sort of pitched towards
writing and towards design.

00:54:28.040 --> 00:54:30.590
And I find that the
menu is a way for me

00:54:30.590 --> 00:54:37.514
to exercise my creativity in a
way that I am passionate about

00:54:37.514 --> 00:54:38.430
and that I believe in.

00:54:38.430 --> 00:54:45.620
And I think it's
empowering to the guest.

00:54:45.620 --> 00:54:48.170
When your drink is
going to depend, really,

00:54:48.170 --> 00:54:52.490
on the ability of the bartender
to take you on the forked path

00:54:52.490 --> 00:54:54.470
that you want, if
the bartender isn't

00:54:54.470 --> 00:54:56.360
great on taking you
on that forked path,

00:54:56.360 --> 00:54:59.330
or the bartender doesn't want
to take you down all the roads

00:54:59.330 --> 00:55:01.910
that are on that path,
you, as the guest,

00:55:01.910 --> 00:55:05.180
may not really get to where
you really wanted to go.

00:55:05.180 --> 00:55:08.810
So it puts a lot of
pressure on the bar staff

00:55:08.810 --> 00:55:12.200
and on the person who trains
the bar staff when you put it

00:55:12.200 --> 00:55:13.010
all on their hands.

00:55:13.010 --> 00:55:15.080
And going back to
the question about,

00:55:15.080 --> 00:55:18.650
do you want me to
ask about the drink,

00:55:18.650 --> 00:55:20.780
not all guests want to
have that much interaction

00:55:20.780 --> 00:55:22.020
with the bartender.

00:55:22.020 --> 00:55:28.490
So going back to my simplistic,
multi-purpose iceberg analogy,

00:55:28.490 --> 00:55:35.510
that menu allows you to deeply
engage and a lot of the path

00:55:35.510 --> 00:55:37.430
we can take you on
and the way that we're

00:55:37.430 --> 00:55:39.342
going to take you,
on your own terms,

00:55:39.342 --> 00:55:41.300
ideally, if you speak
English and read English.

00:55:41.300 --> 00:55:46.760
But it's going to let you become
more empowered, I believe.

00:55:46.760 --> 00:55:50.090
Whereas that sort of
bartender-dependent,

00:55:50.090 --> 00:55:54.800
choose-your-own-adventure style
is highly dependent on the sort

00:55:54.800 --> 00:55:58.550
of knowledge and demeanor and
capabilities of the bartender,

00:55:58.550 --> 00:56:01.070
and the willingness of the
guests to want to engage

00:56:01.070 --> 00:56:05.040
in that way, which, I just
feel like not everyone does.

00:56:05.040 --> 00:56:06.530
So that's my answer.

00:56:06.530 --> 00:56:09.540
My answer would be, I have
a way of doing things.

00:56:09.540 --> 00:56:11.520
And certainly, you
can tell by my answer,

00:56:11.520 --> 00:56:14.660
I can tell you how I like it to
go, and why I like it that way.

00:56:14.660 --> 00:56:17.840
But I have so much respect
for the omakase-style cocktail

00:56:17.840 --> 00:56:19.250
experience done well.

00:56:19.250 --> 00:56:22.360
It is very hard to do well.

00:56:22.360 --> 00:56:23.859
I think we're out
of time, right?

00:56:23.859 --> 00:56:25.400
AMY STARR: We have
time for one more?

00:56:25.400 --> 00:56:25.940
All right.

00:56:25.940 --> 00:56:27.510
Well, thank you, Jim, so much.

00:56:27.510 --> 00:56:28.090
JIM MEEHAN: Thank you very much.

